{"title_page": "Greenan Castle", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n|name           = Greenan Castle\n|location       = [[Ayr, South Ayrshire]], Scotland<br>UK\n|coordinates    = {{coord|55.4386|N|4.6700|W|type:landmark_region:GB-SAY|display=inline,title}}\n|gridref        = \n|image          = Greenan_Shore_and_Castle_-_geograph.org.uk_-_380033.jpg\n|caption        = Greenan Castle from the east\n|map_type       = UK Scotland\n|map_relief     = 1\n|map_caption    = Shown within Scotland\n|map_size       = 150\n|type           = [[Tower house]]\n|built          = 16th century\n|builder        = \n|controlledby   = \n|materials      = \n|height         = \n|used           = \n|condition      = Ruin\n|ownership      = \n|open_to_public = Private\n}}\n'''Greenan Castle''' is a 16th-century ruined [[tower house]], around {{convert|2.5|mi}} south-west of [[Ayr]] in [[South Ayrshire]], Scotland. Situated at the top of a sea cliff, it was originally a [[promontory fort]] converted into a [[motte-and-bailey]] in the 12th century. In the 15th century a tower house was built by the [[Lords of the Isles]], which later passed into the hands of the Kennedy family.<ref name=castles>{{cite web|url=http://www.castlesfortsbattles.co.uk/central_west_scotland/greenan_castle.html|title=Greenan Castle - Argyll, Clyde and Ayrshire - Castles, Forts and Battles|website=www.castlesfortsbattles.co.uk|accessdate=23 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe lands of Greenan were forfeited by [[John MacDonald II, Lord of the Isles|John, Earl of Ross and Lord of the Isles]] in 1476 for treason against [[James III of Scotland|James III]]. In 1493 [[james IV of Scotland|James IV]] granted the Lands of Greenan to William Douglas, son of [[Archibald Douglas, 5th Earl of Angus|Archibald, Earl of Angus]].\n\nThe first known defensive structure on the site was a promontory fort,  probably a fortified farmstead, enclosing around {{convert|1|acre}}. Four concentric curved ditches, each around {{convert|3|m}} wide, cut off the headland with the exception of a single causeway to provide access. It is not known how long this settlement was occupied, but the site was re-used in the twelfth century.<ref name=castles/>\n\nBeside the tower are traces of a walled courtyard and outbuildings\u2014probably stables and a kitchen block, as the small tower has no kitchen within its walls. In this courtyard on the morning of 12 May 1602, Sir Thomas Kennedy of Culzean and his servant, Lancelot Kennedy, mounted their horses to ride to [[Edinburgh]], having spent the night before with Thomas's half-brother, John Kennedy of Baltersan. Just a few miles away in the woods of St Leonards (now a suburb of Ayr), they were ambushed by Thomas Kennedy (of Drummurchie), Thomas Kennedy (brother to the [[Gilbert Kennedy of Bargany and Ardstinchar|Laird of Bargany]]), Walter Muir of Cloncaird, Thomas M'Alexander, Thomas Wallace, a boy called Gilbert Ramsay and a borderer, Williame Irrwing. Sir Thomas was murdered in retaliation for the death of the young Laird of Bargany in December, 1601 at the [[Battle of Brockloch]], near [[Maybole]]. Years later, the Muirs of Auchindrain (father and son) were executed for their \"art and part\" in this murder. The story inspired [[Sir Walter Scott]] to write a short play, \"An Ayrshire Tragedy\".\n\nThe castle passed through various members of the clan before ending up in the hands of Thomas Kennedy, [[Marquess of Ailsa|Earl of Cassillis]] in 1766. Around this time the residential use of the castle seems to have stopped; today the structure is a ruin.<ref name=castles/>\n\n==Notable features==\n[[File:Greenan Castle - geograph.org.uk - 960545.jpg|thumb|Greenan Castle from the west]]\nThe entrance lintel has the inscription, ''JK 1603 FMD'', for John Kennedy of Baltersan and his third wife, Florence MacDowell, who held the lands, Greenan Mill, and salmon fishing rights on the [[River Doon]] at that time.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Alloway Mote]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m90UgNVOS5k Video with commentary and annotation on the history of Greenan Castle]\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Carrick}}\n{{Castles in South Ayrshire}}\n\n\n[[Category:Castles in South Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Category B listed buildings in South Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Listed castles in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Tower houses in Scotland]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=June 2019}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n|name           = Greenan Castle\n|location       = [[Ayr, South Ayrshire]], Scotland<br>UK\n|coordinates    = {{coord|55.4386|N|4.6700|W|type:landmark_region:GB-SAY|display=inline,title}}\n|gridref        = \n|image          = Greenan_Shore_and_Castle_-_geograph.org.uk_-_380033.jpg\n|caption        = Greenan Castle from the east\n|map_type       = UK Scotland\n|map_relief     = 1\n|map_caption    = Shown within Scotland\n|map_size       = 150\n|type           = [[Tower house]]\n|built          = 16th century\n|builder        = \n|controlledby   = \n|materials      = \n|height         = \n|used           = \n|condition      = Ruin\n|ownership      = \n|open_to_public = Private\n}}\n'''Greenan Castle''' is a 16th-century ruined [[tower house]], around {{convert|2.5|mi}} south-west of [[Ayr]] in [[South Ayrshire]], Scotland. Situated at the top of a sea cliff, it was originally a [[promontory fort]] converted into a [[motte-and-bailey]] in the 12th century. In the 15th century a tower house was built by the [[Lords of the Isles]], which later passed into the hands of the Kennedy family.<ref name=castles>{{cite web|url=http://www.castlesfortsbattles.co.uk/central_west_scotland/greenan_castle.html|title=Greenan Castle - Argyll, Clyde and Ayrshire - Castles, Forts and Battles|website=www.castlesfortsbattles.co.uk|accessdate=23 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe lands of Greenan were forfeited by [[John MacDonald II, Lord of the Isles|John, Earl of Ross and Lord of the Isles]] in 1476 for treason against [[James III of Scotland|James III]]. In 1493 [[james IV of Scotland|James IV]] granted the Lands of Greenan to William Douglas, son of [[Archibald Douglas, 5th Earl of Angus|Archibald, Earl of Angus]].\n\nThe first known defensive structure on the site was a promontory fort,  probably a fortified farmstead, enclosing around {{convert|1|acre}}. Four concentric curved ditches, each around {{convert|3|m}} wide, cut off the headland with the exception of a single causeway to provide access. It is not known how long this settlement was occupied, but the site was re-used in the twelfth century.<ref name=castles/>\n\nBeside the tower are traces of a walled courtyard and outbuildings\u2014probably stables and a kitchen block, as the small tower has no kitchen within its walls. In this courtyard on the morning of 12 May 1602, Sir Thomas Kennedy of Culzean and his servant, Lancelot Kennedy, mounted their horses to ride to [[Edinburgh]], having spent the night before with Thomas's half-brother, John Kennedy of Baltersan. Just a few miles away in the woods of St Leonards (now a suburb of Ayr), they were ambushed by Thomas Kennedy (of Drummurchie), Thomas Kennedy (brother to the Laird of Bargany), Walter Muir of Cloncaird, Thomas M'Alexander, Thomas Wallace, a boy called Gilbert Ramsay and a borderer, Williame Irrwing. Sir Thomas was murdered in retaliation for the death of the young Laird of Bargany in December, 1601 at the [[Battle of Brockloch]], near [[Maybole]]. Years later, the Muirs of Auchindrain (father and son) were executed for their \"art and part\" in this murder. The story inspired [[Sir Walter Scott]] to write a short play, \"An Ayrshire Tragedy\".\n\nThe castle passed through various members of the clan before ending up in the hands of Thomas Kennedy, [[Marquess of Ailsa|Earl of Cassillis]] in 1766. Around this time the residential use of the castle seems to have stopped; today the structure is a ruin.<ref name=castles/>\n\n==Notable features==\n[[File:Greenan Castle - geograph.org.uk - 960545.jpg|thumb|Greenan Castle from the west]]\nThe entrance lintel has the inscription, ''JK 1603 FMD'', for John Kennedy of Baltersan and his third wife, Florence MacDowell, who held the lands, Greenan Mill, and salmon fishing rights on the [[River Doon]] at that time.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Alloway Mote]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=m90UgNVOS5k Video with commentary and annotation on the history of Greenan Castle]\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{Carrick}}\n{{Castles in South Ayrshire}}\n\n\n[[Category:Castles in South Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Category B listed buildings in South Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Listed castles in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Tower houses in Scotland]]\n", "name_user": "Unoquha", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greenan_Castle"}
{"title_page": "Tich (singer)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name = Rachel Furner\n| background = solo_singer\n| image = https://www.bing.com/images/search?view=detailV2&ccid=nvA0hwIm&id=C0BEE65219280105AD8426F495D792B6A1D2BB7D&thid=OIP.nvA0hwImOVf0Z-ttQooKWwDhEs&mediaurl=http%3a%2f%2fsitecoreaudioprod.umusicpub.com%2fsitecore_media%2fC34BE421-78FD-49B1-BC2E-0325D320C9A3.jpg%3fcc%3d9122016123855PM&exph=324&expw=243&q=rachel+fruner&simid=607996800684394893&selectedIndex=1&ajaxhist=0\n| birth_name = Rachel Clare Furner\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1992|7|1}}\n| origin = [[Northampton]], England\n| genre = Pop, dance\n| occupation = Singer-songwriter\n| instrument = Piano\n| years_active = 2010\u2013present\n| label = [[All Around the World Productions|AATW]], Universal Music Publishing/JEM Publishing\n}}\n'''Rachel Furner''' is an English singer and songwriter signed to [[Universal Music Publishing Group|Universal Music Publishing]]. She originally performed as an artist under '''Tich''' and as Rachel Furner, signed to [[Mercury Records]].\n\n== Background ==\nFurner was born in Reading and grew up in Northampton. She began to learn to play the piano at the age of six. By age 11 she started to write her own songs about her struggles at school, these experiences inspired her to write a song called Sticks and Stones which she recorded and uploaded to [[Myspace]]. In 2006 she became a member of [[Youth Music Theatre UK]] joining the Missing Melanie company at London's [[Greenwood Theatre]].  At age 15, she got her first record deal with [[Mercury Records]]. She attended [[Northampton High School, Northamptonshire|Northampton High School]] before moving to London at the age of 16.\n\n==Career==\n\nFurner left Mercury Records after two and a half years without releasing any material. Performing under her new artist name Tich, she released an EP titled ''Candelight'', which was released on 20 December 2012 via Gravity. Tich later signed a record deal with [[All Around the World Productions|AATW]]. She supported [[Olly Murs]] across his arena tour in early 2013 and released her debut single \"[[Dumb (Tich song)|Dumb]]\" on the 12th of May 2013 reaching number 23 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. Her second single \"Obsession\" was released on 19 August 2013 and peaked at number 56 in the UK. Her second EP ''Candlelight II'' was released on 8 December 2013. Tich's 3rd single \"Breathe In Breathe Out\" co-written by [[Nick Jonas]] (Jonas Brothers) was released on April 6, 2014.\n\nFurner decided to take a break from being an artist to focus on songwriting, she signed to [[Universal Music Publishing Group|Universal Music Publishing]] out of [[Los Angeles]] in June 2014.\n\nFurner's songwriting credits include [[Little Mix]], [[Jason Derulo]], [[Craig David]], [[The Vamps (British band)|The Vamps]], [[Maggie Lindemann]], [[Sabrina Carpenter]], [[Ward Thomas (band)|Ward Thomas]], [[Ella Henderson]], [[Matt Terry]], [[Frances (musician)|Frances]], [[List of number-one albums of 2017 (Spain)|Sweet California]], Earl, Catherine McGrath and [[Una Healy]].\n\nFurner was presented with a plaque for sales in excess of 1,500,000 for her song \"[[Secret Love Song]]\" performed by Little Mix ft Jason Derulo. \"All We Needed\" co-written by Furner and performed by Craig David was the official [[Children in Need|Children In Need]] single for 2016.\n\n== Songwriting credits ==\n\n'''2020'''\n\n* [[The Shires (duo)|The Shires]] - \"About Last Night\"\n* [[HRVY]] - \"Me Because Of You\"\n* [[Julian Jordan]] - \"Love You Better\"\n\n\n'''2019'''\n* [[Little Mix]] - \"[[One I've Been Missing]]\"\n* [[Professor Green]] - \"Alice\"\n* [[Kato (DJ)|Kato]]- \"Always Been You\"\n* [[Mans Zelmerlow]] -  \"Walk with Me\"\n* [[Ward Thomas (band)|Ward Thomas]] - \"One More Goodbye\"\n* [[Ward Thomas (band)|Ward Thomas]] - \"Ain't That Easy\"\n* [[Ward Thomas (band)|Ward Thomas]] - \"It's Not Just Me\"\n* [[Claire Richards]] - \"Brave\"\n* [[Claire Richards]] - \"Ruins\"\n\n'''2018'''\n*[[Little Mix]] - \"American Boy\"\n*[[Little Mix]] - \"Woman's World\"\n* [[Alice Chater]] - \"Heartbreak Hotel\"\n* [[Craig David]] - \"Focus\"\n* [[Kara Marni]] - \"All Or Nothing\"\n* [[Cailin Russo]] - Joyride\n* [[Craig David]] - \"Love Me Like It's Yesterday\"\n\n'''2017'''\n* [[The Vamps (British band)|The Vamps]] ft [[Maggie Lindemann]] - \"Personal\"\n* [[Matt Terry]] - \"Trouble\"\n* [[Catherine McGrath]] - \"Talk of This Town\n* [[Gray]] ft [[Frances]] - \u201cRoom 101\u201d\n* [[Mike Perry (DJ)|Mike Perry]] ft [[The Vamps (British band)|The Vamps]] & [[Sabrina Carpenter]] - \"Hands\"\n* [[Una Healy]] - \"Staring at the Moon\"\n* [[Una Healy]] - \"Grow Up, Not Old\"\n* [[Frances (musician)|Frances]] - \"Under Our Feet\"\n* [[Earl]] - \"Travelling Heart\"\n\n'''2016'''\n* [[Craig David]] - \"All We Needed\"\n* Sebastian Wibe - \"Fall Like A Hero\"\n* [[Little Mix]] ft [[Jason Derulo]] - \"[[Secret Love Song]]\"\n* [[Little Mix]] - \"[[Secret Love Song|Secret Love Song, Pt. II]]\"\n\n'''2015'''\n*[[Edurne]] - \"Va A Ser Mejor\"\n*[[Sweet California]] - \"Just One\"\n\n==Discography==\n\n=== Extended plays ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:17em;\"| Album details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Candlelight''\n|\n* Released: 20 December 2012<ref name=\"itunes.apple.com\">[https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/candlelight-ep/id578980023 iTunes \u2013 Music \u2013 Candlelight \u2013 EP by Tich]</ref>\n* Label: Gravity Digital\n* Format: Digital download\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Candlelight II''\n|\n* Released: 8 December 2013\n* Label: [[All Around the World Productions|AATW]]\n* Format: Digital download\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"