[[Budapest]], Hungary (2010)\n*{{flagdeco|THA}} [[Bangkok]], Thailand (2005)\n*{{flagdeco|BEL}} [[Antwerp]], Belgium (2011)\n*{{flagdeco|BRA}} [[Salvador, Bahia]], Brazil (2011)\n*{{flagdeco|US}} [[Detroit]], United States (2011)\n*{{flagdeco|US}} [[New York City|New York]], United States (2011)\n*{{flagdeco|IND}} [[Chennai]], India (2015)\n*{{flagdeco|SVN}} [[Maribor]], Slovenia (2017)\n*{{flagdeco|ESP}} [[Telde]], Spain (2018)\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|China}}\n* [[Major national historical and cultural sites (Chongqing)|Major national historical and cultural sites in Chongqing]]\n* [[List of cities in China by population and built-up area]]\n* [[List of twin towns and sister cities in China]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n== References ==\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book |last = Danielson |first = Eric N. |chapter = Chongqing |pages = 325\u2013362 |title = The Three Gorges and the Upper Yangzi |location = Singapore |publisher = Marshall Cavendish/Times Editions |year = 2005 |isbn = 978-981-232-599-0 }}\n* {{cite journal |last = Danielson |first =  Eric N. |title = Revisiting Chongqing: China's Second World War Temporary National Capital |journal = Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society Hong Kong Branch |volume = 45 |year = 2005 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Huang |first = Jiren |script-title = zh:\u8001\u91cd\u5e86\uff1a\u5df4\u5c71\u591c\u8bed |trans-title = Old Chongqing: Ba Mountains Night Rains |series = \u8001\u57ce\u5e02 [''The Old Cities''] |location = Nanjing |publisher = Jiangsu Fine Arts Publishing House |year = 1999 |language = zh }}\n* {{cite book |last = Kapp |first = Robert A. |chapter = Chungking as a Center of Warlord Power, 1926\u20131937 |pages = [https://archive.org/details/chinesecitybetwe00chin/page/143 143\u2013170] |title = The Chinese City Between Two Worlds |chapter-url = https://archive.org/details/chinesecitybetwe00chin |chapter-url-access = registration |editor1 = Mark Elvin |editor2 = G. William Skinner |location = Stanford |publisher = Stanford University Press |year = 1974 }}\n* {{cite book |last = Kapp |first = Robert A. |title = Szechwan and the Chinese Republic: Provincial Militarism and Central Power, 1911\u20131938 |location = New Haven |publisher = Yale University Press |year = 1973 }}\n* {{cite book |author = Liao, Qingyu |title = Chongqing Ge Le Shan Pei Du Yizhi (The Construction of War-time Capital on the Gele Mountain, Chongqing) |location = Chengdu |publisher = Sichuan University Press |year = 2005 }}\n* {{cite book |author = Long, Juncai |title = Sui Yue Ya Feng de Jiyi: Chongqing Kang Zhan Yizhi (Covered Memory of Flowing Years: Site[s] of [the] Anti-Japanese War in Chongqing) |location = Chongqing |publisher = Southwest University Press |year = 2005 }}\n* {{cite book |author = McIsaac, Lee |title = \"The City as Nation: Creating a Wartime Capital in Chongqing,\" in Remaking the Chinese City, 1900\u20131950, ed. by Joseph W. Esherick |location = Honolulu |publisher = University of Hawaii Press |year = 2000 }}\n* {{cite book |author = Xu |title = Chongqing Jiu Ying (Old Photos of Chongqing) |location = Beijing |publisher = People's Fine Arts Publishing House |year = 1998 |author2 = Dongsheng Liu |author3 = Yuchuan }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikivoyage|Chongqing}}\n{{Commons+cat|Chongqing|Chongqing}}\n* [http://www.cq.gov.cn/ Chongqing Municipal Government website]\n\n{{-}}\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Guangzhou]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Historical capitals of China|Wartime Capital of China]]\n|years=21 November 1937 \u2013 5 May 1946\n|dynasty=[[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]]}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Nanjing]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Guangzhou]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Historical capitals of China|Wartime Capital of China]]\n|years=14 October 1949 \u2013 30 November 1949\n|dynasty=[[Republic of China (1912\u20131949)|Republic of China]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Chengdu]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Chongqing}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list=\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[File:Gnome-globe.svg|25px]]{{nbsp}}Geographic locale\n|list =\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre = Chongqing\n|North = [[Shaanxi]]\n|Northeast =\n|East = [[Hubei]]\n|Southeast = [[Hunan]]\n|South = [[Guizhou]]\n|Southwest =\n|West = [[Sichuan]]\n|Northwest =\n}}\n'''[[Geographic coordinate system|Lat. <small>and</small> Long.]] {{Coord|29|33|N|106|34|E|display=inline}}'''\n}}\n{{Province-level divisions of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Metropolitan cities of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Most populous cities in the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Major cities along the Yangtze River}}\n{{World's most populated urban areas}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Chongqing| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Cities in China]]\n[[Category:Municipalities of China]]\n[[Category:Metropolitan areas of China]]\n[[Category:Western China]]\n[[Category:Populated places on the Yangtze River]]\n[[Category:Port cities and towns in China]]\n[[Category:Province-level divisions of China]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in the 5th century BC]]\n[[Category:5th-century BC establishments in China]]\n", "name_user": "Moeng", "label": "safe", "comment": "correction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chongqing"}
{"title_page": "ITunes", "text_new": "{{short description|Apple's media library and media player software}}\n{{About|the application software|the media store|iTunes Store}}\n{{Other uses|iTunes (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{lowercase title}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = iTunes\n| logo = File:ITunes 12.2 logo.png <!-- DO NOT REPLACE WITH SVG, IT HAS AN INACCURATE GRADIENT. The PNG logo is the real logo. -->\n| screenshot = Screenshot of iTunes.png\n| caption = Screenshot of iTunes 12.7.1 on [[Windows 10]]\n| developer = [[Apple Inc.]]\n| released = {{start date and age|2001|1|9}}\n| discontinued = {{end date |2019|6|9}}\n| latest release version = 12.10.5\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2020|3|24}}\n| operating system = {{unbulleted list|[[macOS Mojave]] and earlier|[[Windows 7]] and later}}\n| size = \n| genre = {{Plainlist|\n* [[CD ripper]]\n* [[Digital asset management]]\n* [[Media player (software)|Media player]]\n* [[Optical disc authoring]]\n* [[Tag editor]]\n}}\n| license = [[Freeware]]\n| website = {{URL|https://apple.com/itunes/}}\n}}{{Use mdy dates|date = June 2019}}\n{{macOS topics}}\n\n'''iTunes''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|a\u026a|tj|u\u02d0|n|z}})<ref>{{citation|last=Wells|first=John C.|year=2008|title=Longman Pronunciation Dictionary|edition=3rd|publisher=Longman|page=427|isbn=9781405881180}}</ref> is a [[Media player (software)|media player]], media library, [[Internet radio]] broadcaster, [[mobile device]] management utility, and the client app for [[iTunes Store]], developed by [[Apple Inc.]] It is used to purchase, play, download, and organize digital multimedia, on personal computers running the [[macOS]] and [[Windows]] operating systems, and can be used to [[Ripping|rip]] songs from CDs, as well as play content with the use of dynamic, smart [[Playlist|playlists]]. Options for sound optimizations exist, as well as ways to wirelessly share the iTunes library.\n\nOriginally announced by then-CEO [[Steve Jobs]] on January 9, 2001, iTunes' original and main focus was music, with a library offering organization, collection, and storage of users' music collections. In 2005, however, Apple expanded on the core features with support for digital video, [[podcasts]], [[e-books]], and [[mobile apps]] purchased from [[App Store (iOS)|the iOS App Store]] (the last of which it discontinued in 2017). Further, with the release of the [[iPhone]] in 2007, additional functionality was added to iTunes to enable syncing of the device to a computer and to initiate software updates. Since the release of [[iOS 5]] in 2011, iOS devices have had less reliance on iTunes in order to function, though it can still be used to back up the contents of mobile devices, as well as to share files with personal computers. iTunes was also essential in the functioning of [[Apple TV]] in its early years, to stream content from PCs and Macs with the software.\n\nThough well-received in its early years, iTunes soon received increasingly significant criticism for a [[software bloat|bloated]] user experience, with Apple adopting an all-encompassing feature-set in iTunes rather than sticking to its original music-based purpose. On June 3, 2019, Apple announced that iTunes in [[macOS Catalina]] would be replaced by separate apps, namely [[Apple Music (software)|Music]], [[Podcasts (software)|Podcasts]], and [[Apple TV (software)|TV]]. [[Finder (software)|Finder]] would take over the device management capabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/3/18647182/apple-itunes-podcasts-music-tv-mac-os-wwdc-2019|title=Apple breaks up iTunes, creates separate Podcasts, TV, and Music apps for macOS|last=Carman|first=Ashley|date=2019-06-03|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/itunes-shutting-down-1203231598/|title=Apple Is Officially Killing iTunes, Replacing It With Three Dedicated Media Apps|last=Roettgers|first=Janko|date=2019-06-03|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref> This change would not affect Windows or older macOS versions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/apple-itunes-store-ios-windows-not-going-away-1203231814/|title=Apple\u2019s iTunes Store, iTunes App for Windows Aren\u2019t Going Away|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2019-06-03|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|language=en|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{See also|History of iTunes}}\n[[SoundJam MP]], released by [[Casady & Greene]] in 1998, was renamed \"iTunes\" when [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] purchased it in 2000<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://appleinsider.com/articles/01/01/08/apple_acquires_soundjam_programmer_for_imusic|title=Apple Acquires SoundJam, Programmer for iMusic|last=|first=|date=|work=Apple Insider|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>. The primary developers of the software moved to Apple as part of the acquisition, and simplified SoundJam's user interface, added the ability to burn CDs, and removed its recording feature and [[skin (computing)|skin]] support.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jonathan |last=Seff |title=The Song Is Over for SoundJam |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1002145/11soundjam.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=May 1, 2001 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> The first version of iTunes, promotionally dubbed \"World\u2019s Best and Easiest To Use Jukebox Software\",<ref>{{cite web |first=Jacqui |last=Cheng |title=iTunes through the ages |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2012/11/itunes-through-the-ages/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=November 23, 2012 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> was announced on January 9, 2001.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web |first=Kirk |last=McElhearn |title=15 years of iTunes: A look at Apple\u2019s media app and its influence on an industry |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3019878/software/15-years-of-itunes-a-look-at-apples-media-app-and-its-influence-on-an-industry.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=January 9, 2016 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Subsequent releases of iTunes often coincided with new hardware devices, and gradually included support for new features, including \"smart playlists,\" the [[iTunes Store]], and new audio formats.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\n=== Platform availability ===\nApple released iTunes for Windows in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2003/10/16Apple-Launches-iTunes-for-Windows/|title=Apple Launches iTunes for Windows|date=October 16, 2003|website=Apple Newsroom|publisher=[[Apple Inc.]]|accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> In May 2017, [[Microsoft]] and Apple announced that they would bring iTunes to the [[Microsoft Store (digital)|Microsoft Store]] by the end of that year<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/11/15616594/apple-itunes-windows-store-app-windows-10|title=Apple is bringing iTunes to the Windows Store|last=Warren|first=Tom|date=May 11, 2017|website=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> in order to work on [[Windows 10 S]] devices, which are limited to software available in the Microsoft Store.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/05/11/itunes-in-windows-store/|title=Apple is bringing iTunes to the Windows Store|last=Fingas|first=Jon|date=May 11, 2017|website=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[Oath Inc.]]|accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> However, Apple told ''[[ZDNet]]'' in December that it \"[needs] a little more time to get it right\", and thus won't be available in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/itunes-wont-be-in-the-microsoft-store-this-year/|title=iTunes won't be in the Microsoft Store this year|last=Foley|first=Mary Jo|date=December 15, 2017|website=[[ZDNet]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Apple released the Microsoft Store version on April 26, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/26/17287260/itunes-windows-10-microsoft-store-download|title=iTunes is now available in the Microsoft Store for Windows 10|last=Warren|first=Tom|date=April 26, 2018|work=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==Music library==\niTunes features a music library. Each track has attributes, called [[metadata]], that can be edited by the user, including changing the name of the artist, album, and genre, year of release, artwork, among other additional settings.<ref>{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Elliott |title=Clean up and organize your iTunes music library |url=https://www.cnet.com/how-to/clean-up-and-organize-your-itunes-music-library/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=April 30, 2014 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Miller |title=How I edit track metadata in iTunes |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/2097420/how-i-edit-track-metadata-in-itunes.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=February 13, 2014 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> The software supports importing digital audio tracks that can then be transferred to [[iOS]] devices,<ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Costello |title=How to Import Downloaded Music to iTunes |url=https://www.lifewire.com/add-downloaded-mp3s-to-itunes-4103834 |website=[[Lifewire]] |publisher=[[Dotdash]] |date=October 4, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> as well as supporting [[ripping]] content from CDs.<ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Costello |title=Use iTunes to Copy CDs to Your iPhone or iPod |url=https://www.lifewire.com/copy-cd-to-ipod-iphone-with-itunes-1999496 |website=[[Lifewire]] |publisher=[[Dotdash]] |date=June 13, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Christopher |last=Breen |title=How to rip CDs with iTunes |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1156861/software-graphics/howto-rip-cds.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=January 12, 2011 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> iTunes supports [[WAV]], [[AIFF]], [[Apple Lossless]], [[Advanced Audio Coding|AAC]], and [[MP3]] audio formats.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kirk |last=McElhearn |title=The complete guide to using iTunes with lossless audio |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3053566/software/the-complete-guide-to-using-itunes-with-lossless-audio.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=April 14, 2016 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> It uses the [[Gracenote]] music database to provide track name listings for audio CDs. When users rip content from a CD, iTunes attempts to match songs to the Gracenote service. For self-published CDs, or those from obscure [[record label]]s, iTunes will normally only list tracks as numbered entries (\"Track 1\", \"Track 2\") on an unnamed album by an unknown artist, requiring manual input of data.<ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Costello |title=What To Do When iTunes Doesn't Have CD Names for Your Music |url=https://www.lifewire.com/when-itunes-doesnt-have-cd-names-for-music-2000484 |website=[[Lifewire]] |publisher=[[Dotdash]] |date=March 28, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFile metadata is displayed in users' libraries in columns, including album, artist, genre, composer, and more.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tony |last=Bove |title=How to browse iTunes by artist and album |url=http://www.dummies.com/consumer-electronics/mp3-players/ipod/how-to-browse-itunes-by-artist-and-album/ |website=[[For Dummies]] |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Users can enable or disable different columns, as well as change view settings.<ref>{{cite web |first=Cory |last=Bohon |title=How to change iTunes playlist view |url=http://www.techradar.com/how-to/software/applications/how-to-change-itunes-playlist-view-1302442 |website=[[TechRadar]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |date=August 21, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Special playlists ===\nIntroduced in 2004,<ref>{{cite web |first=Jason |last=Snell |title=iTunes 4.5: Hits and Misses |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1030797/000169.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=April 28, 2004 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> \"Party Shuffle\" selected tracks to play randomly from the library, though users could press a button to skip the current song and go to the next in the list.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kirk |last=McElhearn |title=Doing the iTunes shuffle |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1055239/marchplaylist.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=February 5, 2007 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> The feature was later renamed \"iTunes DJ\",<ref>{{cite web |first=Jason Duaine |last=Hahn |title=Happy Birthday, iTunes: Here's How Apple's Media App Has Changed Over 14 Years |url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2015/01/worst-itunes-changes/ |website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |publisher=[[Verizon Hearst Media Partners]] |date=January 10, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> before being discontinued altogether, replaced by a simpler \"Up Next\" feature that notably lost some of \"iTunes DJ\"'s functionality.<ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Costello |title=Using the Up Next Feature in iTunes |url=https://www.lifewire.com/up-next-feature-in-itunes-4103858 |website=[[Lifewire]] |publisher=[[Dotdash]] |date=February 9, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIntroduced in iTunes 8 in 2008, \"{{visible anchor|Genius}}\" can automatically generate a playlist of songs from the user's library that \"go great together\".<ref>{{cite web |first=David |last=Chartier |title=Apple rocks out, announces new iPods, iTunes 8 |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2008/09/apple-announces-new-products-at-lets-rock-event/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=September 9, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> \"Genius\" transmits information about the user's library to Apple anonymously, and evolves over time to enhance its recommendation system. It can also suggest purchases to fill out \"holes\" in the library.<ref>{{cite web |first=Daniel |last=Dumas |title=Let's rock: Apple unveils new iPod, Genius playlists, HDTV, NBC |url=https://www.wired.com/2008/09/apple-event-let/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=September 9, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> The feature was updated with iTunes 9 in 2009 to offer \"Genius Mixes\", which generated playlists based on specific music genres.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Cox |title=Tip: Update Genius in iTunes 9 to Access Genius Mixes |url=https://www.cultofmac.com/16094/update-genius-in-itunes-9-to-access-genius-mixes/ |website=Cult of Mac |date=September 9, 2009 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Steven |last=Sande |title=iTunes 9 Genius Mixes: You don't need to be a genius to create 'em |url=https://www.engadget.com/2009/09/11/itunes-9-genius-mixes-you-dont-need-to-be-a-genius-to-create/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=September 11, 2009 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"Smart playlists\" are a set of playlists that can be set to automatically filter the library based on a customized list of selection criteria, much like a [[database]] query. Multiple criteria can be entered to manage the smart playlist.<ref>{{cite web |first=Bryan |last=Gardiner |title=Use Smart playlists to keep your iPhone filled with your newest music |url=https://www.wired.com/2013/09/itunes-smart-playlist/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=September 3, 2013 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Selection criteria examples include a genre like [[Christmas music]], songs that haven't been played recently, or songs the user has listened to the most in a time period.<ref>{{cite web |first=Gina |last=Trapani |title=Top 10 iTunes Smart Playlists |url=https://lifehacker.com/355743/top-10-itunes-smart-playlists |website=[[Lifehacker]] |publisher=[[Univision Communications]] |date=February 13, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Library sharing ===\nThrough a \"Home Sharing\" feature, users can share their iTunes library wirelessly.<ref>{{cite web |first=Nik |last=Rawlinson |title=How to share your iTunes music library on a home network |url=https://www.cnet.com/how-to/how-to-share-your-itunes-music-library-on-a-home-network/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=June 13, 2012 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Computer [[Firewall (computing)|firewalls]] must allow network traffic, and users must specifically enable sharing in the iTunes preferences menu. [[iOS]] applications also exist that can transfer content without Internet.<ref>{{cite web |first=Drew |last=Prindle |title=How to share your iTunes library |url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/computing/how-to-share-your-itunes-library/ |website=[[Digital Trends]] |date=April 4, 2013 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Additionally, users can set up a [[network-attached storage]] system, and connect to that storage system through an app.<ref>{{cite web |first=Lance |last=Whitney |title=How to Share Your iTunes Library Among Multiple Devices |url=http://uk.pcmag.com/music-products/87884/news/how-to-share-your-itunes-library-among-multiple-devices |website=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=February 16, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Artwork printing ===\nTo compensate for the \"boring\" design of standard CDs, iTunes can print custom-made [[jewel case]] inserts. After burning a CD from a playlist, one can select that playlist and bring up a dialog box with several print options, including different \"Themes\" of album artworks.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jim |last=Heid |title=Create CD Inserts in iTunes |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1040086/software-graphics/digitalhubnov.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=October 18, 2004 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Sound processing ===\niTunes includes sound processing features, such as [[Equalization (audio)|equalization]], \"sound enhancement\" and [[Crossfade (audio engineering)#Crossfading|crossfade]]. There is also a feature called '''{{visible anchor|Sound Check}}''', which automatically adjusts the playback volume of all songs in the library to the [[audio normalization|same level]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Topher |last=Kessler |title=How to improve sound quality in iTunes |url=https://www.cnet.com/how-to/how-to-improve-sound-quality-in-itunes/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=December 4, 2012 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Kirk |last=McElhearn |title=How to tweak your sound in iTunes and on iOS devices |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3074418/streaming-media/how-to-tweak-your-sound-in-itunes-and-on-ios-devices.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=June 6, 2016 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Video ==\nIn May 2005, video support was introduced to iTunes with the release of iTunes 4.8,<ref>{{cite web |title=iTunes 4.8 adds video support, Yorkdale store photos, more |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/05/05/09/itunes_48_adds_video_support_yorkdale_store_photos_more |website=[[AppleInsider]] |date=May 9, 2005 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> though it was limited to bonus features part of album purchases.<ref>{{cite web |first=Luke |last=Dormehl |title=Today in Apple history: iTunes experiments with video downloads |url=https://www.cultofmac.com/480263/today-apple-history-itunes-experiments-video-downloads/ |website=Cult of Mac |date=May 9, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> The following October, Apple introduced iTunes 6, enabling support for purchasing and viewing video content purchased from the [[iTunes Store]]. At launch, the store offered popular shows from the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] network, including ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'' and ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]'', along with [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[That's So Raven]]'' and ''[[The Suite Life of Zack and Cody]]''. Then-CEO Steve Jobs told the press that \"We\u2019re doing for video what we\u2019ve done for music \u2014 we\u2019re making it easy and affordable to purchase and download, play on your computer, and take with you on your iPod\".<ref name=\"Movies in store\">{{cite web |first=Mathew |last=Honan |title=Apple Releases iTunes 6 |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1047429/itunes6.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=October 12, 2005 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Apple and select film studios introduced \"iTunes Digital Copy\", a feature on select DVDs and Blu-ray discs allowing a digital copy in iTunes and associated media players.<ref>{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Frakes |title=First Look: iTunes Digital Copy |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1131751/digitalcopy.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=January 22, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lionsgate joins Apple's Digital Copy for iTunes program |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/08/03/10/lionsgate_joins_apples_digital_copy_for_itunes_program.html |website=[[AppleInsider]] |date=March 10, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Neil |last=Hughes |title=iTunes Digital Copy redemptions from non-4K Blu-rays appear to support 4K streaming on new Apple TV |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/17/09/22/itunes-digital-copy-redemptions-from-non-4k-blu-rays-appear-to-support-4k-streaming-on-new-apple-tv |website=[[AppleInsider]] |date=September 22, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Podcasts ==\n[[File:Podcasts (iOS).svg|thumb|The icon used by Apple to represent a podcast]]\nIn June 2005, Apple updated iTunes with support for [[podcast]]s.<ref>{{cite web |first=Pete |last=Naughton |title=The 10 best ever podcasts |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11668186/The-10-best-ever-podcasts.html |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] |date=June 14, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Podcasts how-to\">{{cite web |first=Cyrus |last=Farivar |title=iTunes 4.9 First Look: Apple takes on Podcasting |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1045522/podcastingfirstlook.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=June 28, 2005 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Users can subscribe to podcasts, change update frequency, define how many episodes to download and how many to delete.<ref name=\"Podcasts how-to\" />\n\nSimilar to [[iTunes#Special playlists|songs]], \"Smart playlists\" can be used to control podcasts in a playlist, setting criteria such as date and number of times listened to.<ref>{{cite web |first=Mike |last=Schramm |title=How to: Create a smart podcast playlist in iTunes |url=https://www.engadget.com/2008/02/01/how-to-create-a-smart-podcast-playlist-in-itunes/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=February 1, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n{{Main|Apple Books}}\nIn January 2010, Apple announced the [[iPad]] [[Tablet computer|tablet]], and along with it, a new app for it called [[Apple Books]] (previously known as iBooks). The app allowed users to purchase [[e-book]]s from the [[iTunes Store]], manage them through iTunes, and transfer the content to their iPad.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Bobbie |last1=Johnson |first2=Charles |last2=Arthur |title=Apple iPad: the wait is over \u2013 but is it future of media or oversized phone? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2010/jan/27/apple-ipad-tablet-computer-kindle |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=January 27, 2010 |accessdate=February 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Apps ==\n{{Main|App Store (iOS)}}\nOn July 10, 2008, Apple introduced native [[mobile app]]s for its [[iOS]] operating system. On iOS, a dedicated App Store application served as the storefront for browsing, purchasing and managing applications, whereas iTunes on computers had a dedicated section for apps rather than a separate app.<ref>{{cite web |first=Lex |last=Friedman |title=The App Store turns five: A look back and forward |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/2043841/the-app-store-turns-five-a-look-back-and-forward.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=July 8, 2013 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> In September 2017, Apple updated iTunes to version 12.7, removing the App Store section in the process.<ref name=\"cutting the bloat\">{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Welch |title=Apple starts cutting the bloat from iTunes by removing iOS App Store |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/12/16298988/apple-itunes-desktop-update-removes-app-store |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jake |last=Smith |title=Apple's iTunes removes iOS App Store from desktop version |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/apple-removes-ios-app-store-from-desktop-versions-of-itunes/ |website=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=September 13, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> However, the following month, iTunes 12.6.3 was also released, retaining the App Store, with ''9to5Mac'' noting that the secondary release was positioned by Apple as \"necessary for some businesses performing internal app deployments\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Benjamin |last=Mayo |title=Apple still offers an iTunes version with App Store, Ringtones and other features removed in \u2018focused\u2019 iTunes 12.7 |url=https://9to5mac.com/2017/10/09/apple-itunes-apps-focused-removed-stopgap/ |website=[[9to5Mac]] |date=October 9, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Hardwick |title=Apple Quietly Releases iTunes 12.6.3 With Built-In App Store |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/10/09/apple-itunes-with-app-store-included/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=October 9, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== iTunes Store ==\n{{Main|iTunes Store}}\nOn April 28, 2003, Apple introduced the [[iTunes Store]], then-named \"iTunes Music Store\". It allowed users to buy and download songs, with 200,000 tracks available at launch. In its first week, customers bought more than one million songs.<ref>{{cite web |first=Brian X. |last=Chen |title=April 28, 2003: Apple opens iTunes Store |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/04/0428itunes-music-store-opens/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=April 28, 2010 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Music purchased was protected by [[FairPlay]], an [[encryption]] layer referred to as [[digital rights management]] (DRM).<ref>\n{{cite web |first=Daniel Eran |last=Dilger |title=How FairPlay Works: Apple's iTunes DRM Dilemma |url=http://www.roughlydrafted.com/RD/RDM.Tech.Q1.07/2A351C60-A4E5-4764-A083-FF8610E66A46.html |website=RoughlyDrafted |date=February 26, 2007 |access-date=December 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927030905/http://www.roughlydrafted.com/RD/RDM.Tech.Q1.07/2A351C60-A4E5-4764-A083-FF8610E66A46.html |archive-date=2017-09-27 |url-status=dead |df= }}\n</ref> The use of DRM, which limited devices capable of playing purchased files,<ref>{{cite web |first=Dave |last=Hamilton |title=How iTunes Movie DRM-Removal Software Keeps Me Honest |url=https://www.macobserver.com/tmo/article/itunes-drm-removal-keeps-me-legal |website=The Mac Observer |date=September 2, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> sparked efforts to remove the protection mechanism.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jim |last=Tanous |title=The iTunes DRM Removal Saga: NoteBurner and a Look Back at Requiem |url=https://www.tekrevue.com/itunes-drm-removal/ |website=TekRevue |date=September 2, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Eventually, after [[Thoughts on Music|an open letter]] to the music industry by then-CEO Steve Jobs in February 2007,<ref>{{cite web |first=Arnold |last=Kim |title=Steve Jobs 'Thoughts on Music' - Asks for No Digital Rights Management |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2007/02/06/steve-jobs-thoughts-on-music/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=February 6, 2007 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Apple introduced a selection of DRM-free music in the iTunes Store in April 2007,<ref>{{cite web |first=Michael |last=Arrington |authorlink=Michael Arrington |title=EMI, Apple To Sell DRM-Free Music for $1.29/song |url=https://techcrunch.com/2007/04/02/emi-apple-are-announcing-sale-of-non-drm-music/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=April 2, 2007 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> followed by its entire music catalog without DRM in January 2009.<ref>{{cite web |first=Bobbie |last=Johnson |title=Apple drops DRM copy protection from millions of iTunes songs |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2009/jan/06/apple-drops-itunes-copy-protection |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=January 6, 2009 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2005, Apple announced that movies and television shows would become available through its iTunes Store, employing the DRM protection.<ref name=\"Movies in store\" />\n\n=== iTunes U ===\nIn May 2007, Apple announced the launch of \"iTunes U\" via the [[iTunes Store]], which delivers university lectures from top U.S. colleges.<ref>{{cite web |first=Peter |last=Cohen |title=iTunes U comes to the iTunes Store |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1058118/itunesu.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=May 30, 2007 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=McNulty |title=iTunes U comes to the iTunes Store |url=https://www.engadget.com/2007/05/30/itunes-u-comes-to-the-itunes-store/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=May 30, 2007 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWith iTunes version 12.7 in August 2017, iTunes U collections became a part of the [[iTunes#Podcasts|Podcasts]] app.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Hardwick |title=iTunes U Collections Will Move to Apple Podcasts From September |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/08/21/itunes-u-collections-to-apple-podcasts-september/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=August 21, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== iTunes in the Cloud and iTunes Match ===\nIn June 2011, Apple announced \"iTunes in the Cloud\", in which music purchases were stored on Apple's servers and made available for automatic downloading on new devices. For music the user owns, such as content ripped from CDs, the company introduced \"iTunes Match\", a feature that can upload content to Apple's servers, match it to its catalog, change the quality to 256kbit/s [[Advanced Audio Coding|AAC]] format, and make it available to other devices.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Ziegler |title=iTunes in the Cloud beta available today, iTunes Match lets you 'upload' the tracks you already own for $24.99 a year |url=https://www.theverge.com/2011/06/06/itunes-cloud-announced/ |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=June 6, 2011 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Courtney Boyd |last=Myers |title=iTunes Match: Apple announces its cloud based music service |url=https://thenextweb.com/wwdc/2011/06/06/apple-announces-itunes-in-the-cloud/ |website=The Next Web |date=June 6, 2011 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Internet radio and music streaming ==\n{{Main|iTunes Radio|Apple Music}}\nWhen iTunes was first released, it came with support for the [[Kerbango]] [[Internet radio]] tuner service.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tyler |last=Gray |title=Why Apple\u2019s iTunes Is Still Fundamentally Flawed, Even In iOS 7 |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3017628/why-apples-itunes-is-still-fundamentally-flawed-even-in-ios-7 |website=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] |publisher=Mansueto Ventures |date=September 18, 2013 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> In June 2013, the company announced [[iTunes Radio]], a free music streaming service.<ref>{{cite web |first=Doug |last=Gross |title=Apple arrives (late?) to music streaming with iTunes Radio |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/06/10/tech/web/itunes-radio-apple-wwdc/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting System]] |date=June 11, 2013 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> In June 2015, Apple announced [[Apple Music]], its paid music streaming service, and subsequently rebranded iTunes Radio into [[Beats 1]], a radio station accompanying Apple Music.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Ben |last1=Popper |first2=Micah |last2=Singleton |title=Apple announces its streaming music service, Apple Music |url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/6/8/8729481/apple-music-streaming-service-wwdc-15 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=June 8, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== iPhone connectivity ==\n{{Update section|date=March 2020|reson=iPhone Backup, Restore, USB hotspot are amongst features that require iTunes to be installed on Windows.}}\niTunes was used to activate early [[iPhone]] models. Beginning with the [[iPhone 3G]] in June 2008, activation did not require iTunes, making use of activation at point of sale.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jonathan |last=Geller |title=iPhone 3G: the details you never wanted to know |url=http://bgr.com/2008/06/09/iphone-3g-the-details-you-never-wanted-to-know/ |website=[[Boy Genius Report|BGR]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |date=June 9, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Ping ==\n{{Main|iTunes Ping}}\nWith the release of iTunes 10 in September 2010, Apple announced [[iTunes Ping]], which then-CEO Steve Jobs described as \"social music discovery\". It had features reminiscent of [[Facebook]], including profiles and the ability to follow other users.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chloe |last=Albanesius |title=Apple Goes Social with 'Ping' Inside iTunes 10 |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2368579,00.asp |website=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=September 1, 2010 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Ping was discontinued in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web |first=Angela |last=Moscaritolo |title=Apple Shutting Down iTunes Ping on Sept. 30 |url=http://uk.pcmag.com/music-products/60441/news/apple-shutting-down-itunes-ping-on-sept-30 |website=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=September 13, 2012 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\n\n=== Security ===\n''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' reported in November 2011 that Apple had been aware of a [[security vulnerability]] since 2008 that would let unauthorized third parties install \"updates\" to users' iTunes software. Apple fixed the issue prior to the ''Telegraph''{{'}}s report, and told the media that \"The security and privacy of our users is extremely important\", though this was questioned by security researcher [[Brian Krebs]], who told the publication that \"A prominent security researcher warned Apple about this dangerous vulnerability in mid-2008, yet the company waited more than 1,200 days to fix the flaw\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Christopher |last=Williams |title=Apple iTunes flaw 'allowed government spying for 3 years' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/apple/8912714/Apple-iTunes-flaw-allowed-government-spying-for-3-years.html |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] |date=November 24, 2011 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Software bloat ===\niTunes has been repeatedly accused of being [[Software bloat|bloated]] as part of Apple's efforts to turn it from a music player to an all-encompassing multimedia platform.<ref name=\"cutting the bloat\" /><ref>{{cite web |first=Amy |last=Wang |title=iTunes is 13 years old\u2014and it\u2019s still awful |url=https://qz.com/666078/itunes-is-13-years-old-today-and-its-still-awful/ |website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] |publisher=[[Atlantic Media]] |date=April 28, 2016 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Ben |last=Lovejoy |title=Opinion: iTunes is now so clunky the only safe solution is to nuke it from orbit |url=https://9to5mac.com/2015/07/28/opinion-itunes-nuke-from-orbit/ |website=9to5Mac |date=July 28, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Robinson |last=Meyer |title=iTunes Really Is That Bad |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/07/why-is-itunes-so-bad/399833/ |website=[[The Atlantic]] |publisher=[[Emerson Collective]] |date=July 29, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Gilbertson |title=The top ten reasons iTunes sucks |url=https://www.wired.com/2008/11/the_top_ten_reasons_itunes_sucks/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=November 5, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Former ''[[PC World]]'' editor [[Ed Bott]] accused the company of hypocrisy in its advertising attacks on [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] for similar practices.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ed |last=Bott |title=Slimming down the bloated iTunes installer |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/slimming-down-the-bloated-itunes-installer/ |website=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=October 3, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the announcement of [[macOS Catalina]], [[Craig Federighi]] addressed the evolution of iTunes, and joked about the potential to include Email, Calendar, and Safari in iTunes before announcing iTunes's separation into independent apps, Apple Music, Apple TV, and more.\n\n==See also==\n* [[iTunes Festival]]\n* [[iTunes Store]]\n* [[iTunes version history]]\n* [[AirPlay]]\n* [[List of audio conversion software]]\n* [[Comparison of iPod managers]]\n* [[Digital distribution|Distribution Into iTunes]]\n* [[FairPlay]]\n* [[Feed aggregator]]s:\n** [[Comparison of feed aggregators|Feed aggregators, comparison]]\n** [[List of feed aggregators|Feed aggregators, List]]\n* [[Comparison of audio player software|Media players, comparison]]\n* [[Music visualization]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikibooks|iTunes}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.apple.com/itunes|iTunes}} \u2013 official site\n\n{{navboxes\n|title=iTunes\n|list1=\n{{Podcast distribution platforms}}\n{{Media player (application software)}}\n{{Apple software}}\n{{Apple software on Windows}}\n{{macOS}}\n{{Aggregators}}\n{{Apple}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:ITunes|01]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. services]]\n[[Category:Online music database clients]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2001]]\n[[Category:Products and services discontinued in 2019]]\n[[Category:2001 software]]\n[[Category:Apple Inc. software]]\n[[Category:IOS software]]\n[[Category:IPod software]]\n[[Category:Mobile device management software]]\n[[Category:MacOS CD ripping software]]\n[[Category:Podcasting software]]\n[[Category:Internet properties established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Internet properties disestablished in 2019]]\n[[Category:Jukebox-style media players]]\n[[Category:Mac OS media players]]\n[[Category:MacOS media players]]\n[[Category:Music streaming services]]\n[[Category:Tag editors]]\n[[Category:Transactional video on demand]]\n[[Category:Windows CD ripping software]]\n[[Category:Windows CD/DVD writing software]]\n[[Category:Windows media players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Apple's media library and media player software}}\n{{About|the application software|the media store|iTunes Store}}\n{{Other uses|iTunes (disambiguation)}}\n{{pp-move-indef}}\n{{lowercase title}}\n{{Infobox software\n| name = iTunes\n| logo = File:ITunes 12.2 logo.png <!-- DO NOT REPLACE WITH SVG, IT HAS AN INACCURATE GRADIENT. The PNG logo is the real logo. -->\n| screenshot = Screenshot of iTunes.png\n| caption = Screenshot of iTunes 12.7.1 on [[Windows 10]]\n| developer = [[Apple Inc.]]\n| released = {{start date and age|2001|1|9}}\n| discontinued = {{end date |2019|6|9}}\n| latest release version = 12.10.5\n| latest release date = {{Start date and age|2020|3|24}}\n| operating system = {{unbulleted list|[[macOS Mojave]] and earlier|[[Windows 7]] and later}}\n| size = \n| genre = {{Plainlist|\n* [[CD ripper]]\n* [[Digital asset management]]\n* [[Media player (software)|Media player]]\n* [[Optical disc authoring]]\n* [[Tag editor]]\n}}\n| license = [[Freeware]]\n| website = {{URL|https://apple.com/itunes/}}\n}}{{Use mdy dates|date = June 2019}}\n{{macOS topics}}\n\n'''iTunes''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|a\u026a|tj|u\u02d0|n|z}})<ref>{{citation|last=Wells|first=John C.|year=2008|title=Longman Pronunciation Dictionary|edition=3rd|publisher=Longman|page=427|isbn=9781405881180}}</ref> is a [[Media player (software)|media player]], media library, [[Internet radio]] broadcaster, [[mobile device]] management utility, and the client app for [[iTunes Store]], developed by [[Apple Inc.]] It is used to purchase, play, download, and organize digital multimedia, on personal computers running the [[macOS]] and [[Windows]] operating systems, and can be used to [[Ripping|rip]] songs from CDs, as well as play content with the use of dynamic, smart [[Playlist|playlists]]. Options for sound optimizations exist, as well as ways to wirelessly share the iTunes library.\n\nOriginally announced by then-CEO [[Steve Jobs]] on January 9, 2001, iTunes' original and main focus was music, with a library offering organization, collection, and storage of users' music collections. In 2005, however, Apple expanded on the core features with support for digital video, [[podcasts]], [[e-books]], and [[mobile apps]] purchased from [[App Store (iOS)|the iOS App Store]] (the last of which it discontinued in 2017). The [[iPhone (1st generation)|original]] [[iPhone]] required iTunes for activation. Until the release of [[iOS 5]] in 2011, iTunes was required for updating mobile apps. Newer iOS devices have less reliance on iTunes in order to function, though it can still be used to back up the contents of mobile devices, as well as to share files with personal computers.\n\nThough well-received in its early years, iTunes soon received increasingly significant criticism for a [[software bloat|bloated]] user experience, with Apple adopting an all-encompassing feature-set in iTunes rather than sticking to its original music-based purpose. On June 3, 2019, Apple announced that iTunes in [[macOS Catalina]] would be replaced by separate apps, namely [[Apple Music (software)|Music]], [[Podcasts (software)|Podcasts]], and [[Apple TV (software)|TV]]. [[Finder (software)|Finder]] would take over the device management capabilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/6/3/18647182/apple-itunes-podcasts-music-tv-mac-os-wwdc-2019|title=Apple breaks up iTunes, creates separate Podcasts, TV, and Music apps for macOS|last=Carman|first=Ashley|date=2019-06-03|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/itunes-shutting-down-1203231598/|title=Apple Is Officially Killing iTunes, Replacing It With Three Dedicated Media Apps|last=Roettgers|first=Janko|date=2019-06-03|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref> This change would not affect Windows or older macOS versions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/digital/news/apple-itunes-store-ios-windows-not-going-away-1203231814/|title=Apple\u2019s iTunes Store, iTunes App for Windows Aren\u2019t Going Away|last=Spangler|first=Todd|date=2019-06-03|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|language=en|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n{{See also|History of iTunes}}\n[[SoundJam MP]], released by [[Casady & Greene]] in 1998, was renamed \"iTunes\" when [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] purchased it in 2000<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://appleinsider.com/articles/01/01/08/apple_acquires_soundjam_programmer_for_imusic|title=Apple Acquires SoundJam, Programmer for iMusic|last=|first=|date=|work=Apple Insider|access-date=|url-status=live}}</ref>. The primary developers of the software moved to Apple as part of the acquisition, and simplified SoundJam's user interface, added the ability to burn CDs, and removed its recording feature and [[skin (computing)|skin]] support.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jonathan |last=Seff |title=The Song Is Over for SoundJam |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1002145/11soundjam.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=May 1, 2001 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> The first version of iTunes, promotionally dubbed \"World\u2019s Best and Easiest To Use Jukebox Software\",<ref>{{cite web |first=Jacqui |last=Cheng |title=iTunes through the ages |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2012/11/itunes-through-the-ages/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=November 23, 2012 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> was announced on January 9, 2001.<ref name=\"History\">{{cite web |first=Kirk |last=McElhearn |title=15 years of iTunes: A look at Apple\u2019s media app and its influence on an industry |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3019878/software/15-years-of-itunes-a-look-at-apples-media-app-and-its-influence-on-an-industry.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=January 9, 2016 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Subsequent releases of iTunes often coincided with new hardware devices, and gradually included support for new features, including \"smart playlists,\" the [[iTunes Store]], and new audio formats.<ref name=\"History\" />\n\n=== Platform availability ===\nApple released iTunes for Windows in 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.apple.com/newsroom/2003/10/16Apple-Launches-iTunes-for-Windows/|title=Apple Launches iTunes for Windows|date=October 16, 2003|website=Apple Newsroom|publisher=[[Apple Inc.]]|accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> In May 2017, [[Microsoft]] and Apple announced that they would bring iTunes to the [[Microsoft Store (digital)|Microsoft Store]] by the end of that year<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/11/15616594/apple-itunes-windows-store-app-windows-10|title=Apple is bringing iTunes to the Windows Store|last=Warren|first=Tom|date=May 11, 2017|website=[[The Verge]]|publisher=[[Vox Media]]|accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> in order to work on [[Windows 10 S]] devices, which are limited to software available in the Microsoft Store.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/05/11/itunes-in-windows-store/|title=Apple is bringing iTunes to the Windows Store|last=Fingas|first=Jon|date=May 11, 2017|website=[[Engadget]]|publisher=[[Oath Inc.]]|accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> However, Apple told ''[[ZDNet]]'' in December that it \"[needs] a little more time to get it right\", and thus won't be available in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/itunes-wont-be-in-the-microsoft-store-this-year/|title=iTunes won't be in the Microsoft Store this year|last=Foley|first=Mary Jo|date=December 15, 2017|website=[[ZDNet]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Apple released the Microsoft Store version on April 26, 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/4/26/17287260/itunes-windows-10-microsoft-store-download|title=iTunes is now available in the Microsoft Store for Windows 10|last=Warren|first=Tom|date=April 26, 2018|work=[[The Verge]]|access-date=2018-04-26}}</ref>\n\n==Music library==\niTunes features a music library. Each track has attributes, called [[metadata]], that can be edited by the user, including changing the name of the artist, album, and genre, year of release, artwork, among other additional settings.<ref>{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Elliott |title=Clean up and organize your iTunes music library |url=https://www.cnet.com/how-to/clean-up-and-organize-your-itunes-music-library/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=April 30, 2014 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Miller |title=How I edit track metadata in iTunes |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/2097420/how-i-edit-track-metadata-in-itunes.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=February 13, 2014 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> The software supports importing digital audio tracks that can then be transferred to [[iOS]] devices,<ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Costello |title=How to Import Downloaded Music to iTunes |url=https://www.lifewire.com/add-downloaded-mp3s-to-itunes-4103834 |website=[[Lifewire]] |publisher=[[Dotdash]] |date=October 4, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> as well as supporting [[ripping]] content from CDs.<ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Costello |title=Use iTunes to Copy CDs to Your iPhone or iPod |url=https://www.lifewire.com/copy-cd-to-ipod-iphone-with-itunes-1999496 |website=[[Lifewire]] |publisher=[[Dotdash]] |date=June 13, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Christopher |last=Breen |title=How to rip CDs with iTunes |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1156861/software-graphics/howto-rip-cds.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=January 12, 2011 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> iTunes supports [[WAV]], [[AIFF]], [[Apple Lossless]], [[Advanced Audio Coding|AAC]], and [[MP3]] audio formats.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kirk |last=McElhearn |title=The complete guide to using iTunes with lossless audio |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3053566/software/the-complete-guide-to-using-itunes-with-lossless-audio.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=April 14, 2016 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> It uses the [[Gracenote]] music database to provide track name listings for audio CDs. When users rip content from a CD, iTunes attempts to match songs to the Gracenote service. For self-published CDs, or those from obscure [[record label]]s, iTunes will normally only list tracks as numbered entries (\"Track 1\", \"Track 2\") on an unnamed album by an unknown artist, requiring manual input of data.<ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Costello |title=What To Do When iTunes Doesn't Have CD Names for Your Music |url=https://www.lifewire.com/when-itunes-doesnt-have-cd-names-for-music-2000484 |website=[[Lifewire]] |publisher=[[Dotdash]] |date=March 28, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFile metadata is displayed in users' libraries in columns, including album, artist, genre, composer, and more.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tony |last=Bove |title=How to browse iTunes by artist and album |url=http://www.dummies.com/consumer-electronics/mp3-players/ipod/how-to-browse-itunes-by-artist-and-album/ |website=[[For Dummies]] |publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons]] |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Users can enable or disable different columns, as well as change view settings.<ref>{{cite web |first=Cory |last=Bohon |title=How to change iTunes playlist view |url=http://www.techradar.com/how-to/software/applications/how-to-change-itunes-playlist-view-1302442 |website=[[TechRadar]] |publisher=[[Future plc]] |date=August 21, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Special playlists ===\nIntroduced in 2004,<ref>{{cite web |first=Jason |last=Snell |title=iTunes 4.5: Hits and Misses |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1030797/000169.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=April 28, 2004 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> \"Party Shuffle\" selected tracks to play randomly from the library, though users could press a button to skip the current song and go to the next in the list.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kirk |last=McElhearn |title=Doing the iTunes shuffle |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1055239/marchplaylist.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=February 5, 2007 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> The feature was later renamed \"iTunes DJ\",<ref>{{cite web |first=Jason Duaine |last=Hahn |title=Happy Birthday, iTunes: Here's How Apple's Media App Has Changed Over 14 Years |url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2015/01/worst-itunes-changes/ |website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |publisher=[[Verizon Hearst Media Partners]] |date=January 10, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> before being discontinued altogether, replaced by a simpler \"Up Next\" feature that notably lost some of \"iTunes DJ\"'s functionality.<ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Costello |title=Using the Up Next Feature in iTunes |url=https://www.lifewire.com/up-next-feature-in-itunes-4103858 |website=[[Lifewire]] |publisher=[[Dotdash]] |date=February 9, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIntroduced in iTunes 8 in 2008, \"{{visible anchor|Genius}}\" can automatically generate a playlist of songs from the user's library that \"go great together\".<ref>{{cite web |first=David |last=Chartier |title=Apple rocks out, announces new iPods, iTunes 8 |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2008/09/apple-announces-new-products-at-lets-rock-event/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=September 9, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> \"Genius\" transmits information about the user's library to Apple anonymously, and evolves over time to enhance its recommendation system. It can also suggest purchases to fill out \"holes\" in the library.<ref>{{cite web |first=Daniel |last=Dumas |title=Let's rock: Apple unveils new iPod, Genius playlists, HDTV, NBC |url=https://www.wired.com/2008/09/apple-event-let/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=September 9, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> The feature was updated with iTunes 9 in 2009 to offer \"Genius Mixes\", which generated playlists based on specific music genres.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Cox |title=Tip: Update Genius in iTunes 9 to Access Genius Mixes |url=https://www.cultofmac.com/16094/update-genius-in-itunes-9-to-access-genius-mixes/ |website=Cult of Mac |date=September 9, 2009 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Steven |last=Sande |title=iTunes 9 Genius Mixes: You don't need to be a genius to create 'em |url=https://www.engadget.com/2009/09/11/itunes-9-genius-mixes-you-dont-need-to-be-a-genius-to-create/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=September 11, 2009 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n\"Smart playlists\" are a set of playlists that can be set to automatically filter the library based on a customized list of selection criteria, much like a [[database]] query. Multiple criteria can be entered to manage the smart playlist.<ref>{{cite web |first=Bryan |last=Gardiner |title=Use Smart playlists to keep your iPhone filled with your newest music |url=https://www.wired.com/2013/09/itunes-smart-playlist/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=September 3, 2013 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Selection criteria examples include a genre like [[Christmas music]], songs that haven't been played recently, or songs the user has listened to the most in a time period.<ref>{{cite web |first=Gina |last=Trapani |title=Top 10 iTunes Smart Playlists |url=https://lifehacker.com/355743/top-10-itunes-smart-playlists |website=[[Lifehacker]] |publisher=[[Univision Communications]] |date=February 13, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Library sharing ===\nThrough a \"Home Sharing\" feature, users can share their iTunes library wirelessly.<ref>{{cite web |first=Nik |last=Rawlinson |title=How to share your iTunes music library on a home network |url=https://www.cnet.com/how-to/how-to-share-your-itunes-music-library-on-a-home-network/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=June 13, 2012 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Computer [[Firewall (computing)|firewalls]] must allow network traffic, and users must specifically enable sharing in the iTunes preferences menu. [[iOS]] applications also exist that can transfer content without Internet.<ref>{{cite web |first=Drew |last=Prindle |title=How to share your iTunes library |url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/computing/how-to-share-your-itunes-library/ |website=[[Digital Trends]] |date=April 4, 2013 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Additionally, users can set up a [[network-attached storage]] system, and connect to that storage system through an app.<ref>{{cite web |first=Lance |last=Whitney |title=How to Share Your iTunes Library Among Multiple Devices |url=http://uk.pcmag.com/music-products/87884/news/how-to-share-your-itunes-library-among-multiple-devices |website=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=February 16, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Artwork printing ===\nTo compensate for the \"boring\" design of standard CDs, iTunes can print custom-made [[jewel case]] inserts. After burning a CD from a playlist, one can select that playlist and bring up a dialog box with several print options, including different \"Themes\" of album artworks.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jim |last=Heid |title=Create CD Inserts in iTunes |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1040086/software-graphics/digitalhubnov.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=October 18, 2004 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Sound processing ===\niTunes includes sound processing features, such as [[Equalization (audio)|equalization]], \"sound enhancement\" and [[Crossfade (audio engineering)#Crossfading|crossfade]]. There is also a feature called '''{{visible anchor|Sound Check}}''', which automatically adjusts the playback volume of all songs in the library to the [[audio normalization|same level]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Topher |last=Kessler |title=How to improve sound quality in iTunes |url=https://www.cnet.com/how-to/how-to-improve-sound-quality-in-itunes/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=December 4, 2012 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Kirk |last=McElhearn |title=How to tweak your sound in iTunes and on iOS devices |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/3074418/streaming-media/how-to-tweak-your-sound-in-itunes-and-on-ios-devices.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=June 6, 2016 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Video ==\nIn May 2005, video support was introduced to iTunes with the release of iTunes 4.8,<ref>{{cite web |title=iTunes 4.8 adds video support, Yorkdale store photos, more |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/05/05/09/itunes_48_adds_video_support_yorkdale_store_photos_more |website=[[AppleInsider]] |date=May 9, 2005 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> though it was limited to bonus features part of album purchases.<ref>{{cite web |first=Luke |last=Dormehl |title=Today in Apple history: iTunes experiments with video downloads |url=https://www.cultofmac.com/480263/today-apple-history-itunes-experiments-video-downloads/ |website=Cult of Mac |date=May 9, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> The following October, Apple introduced iTunes 6, enabling support for purchasing and viewing video content purchased from the [[iTunes Store]]. At launch, the store offered popular shows from the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] network, including ''[[Desperate Housewives]]'' and ''[[Lost (TV series)|Lost]]'', along with [[Disney Channel]] series ''[[That's So Raven]]'' and ''[[The Suite Life of Zack and Cody]]''. Then-CEO Steve Jobs told the press that \"We\u2019re doing for video what we\u2019ve done for music \u2014 we\u2019re making it easy and affordable to purchase and download, play on your computer, and take with you on your iPod\".<ref name=\"Movies in store\">{{cite web |first=Mathew |last=Honan |title=Apple Releases iTunes 6 |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1047429/itunes6.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=October 12, 2005 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Apple and select film studios introduced \"iTunes Digital Copy\", a feature on select DVDs and Blu-ray discs allowing a digital copy in iTunes and associated media players.<ref>{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Frakes |title=First Look: iTunes Digital Copy |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1131751/digitalcopy.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=January 22, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lionsgate joins Apple's Digital Copy for iTunes program |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/08/03/10/lionsgate_joins_apples_digital_copy_for_itunes_program.html |website=[[AppleInsider]] |date=March 10, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Neil |last=Hughes |title=iTunes Digital Copy redemptions from non-4K Blu-rays appear to support 4K streaming on new Apple TV |url=http://appleinsider.com/articles/17/09/22/itunes-digital-copy-redemptions-from-non-4k-blu-rays-appear-to-support-4k-streaming-on-new-apple-tv |website=[[AppleInsider]] |date=September 22, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Podcasts ==\n[[File:Podcasts (iOS).svg|thumb|The icon used by Apple to represent a podcast]]\nIn June 2005, Apple updated iTunes with support for [[podcast]]s.<ref>{{cite web |first=Pete |last=Naughton |title=The 10 best ever podcasts |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11668186/The-10-best-ever-podcasts.html |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] |date=June 14, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Podcasts how-to\">{{cite web |first=Cyrus |last=Farivar |title=iTunes 4.9 First Look: Apple takes on Podcasting |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1045522/podcastingfirstlook.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=June 28, 2005 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Users can subscribe to podcasts, change update frequency, define how many episodes to download and how many to delete.<ref name=\"Podcasts how-to\" />\n\nSimilar to [[iTunes#Special playlists|songs]], \"Smart playlists\" can be used to control podcasts in a playlist, setting criteria such as date and number of times listened to.<ref>{{cite web |first=Mike |last=Schramm |title=How to: Create a smart podcast playlist in iTunes |url=https://www.engadget.com/2008/02/01/how-to-create-a-smart-podcast-playlist-in-itunes/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=February 1, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n{{Main|Apple Books}}\nIn January 2010, Apple announced the [[iPad]] [[Tablet computer|tablet]], and along with it, a new app for it called [[Apple Books]] (previously known as iBooks). The app allowed users to purchase [[e-book]]s from the [[iTunes Store]], manage them through iTunes, and transfer the content to their iPad.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Bobbie |last1=Johnson |first2=Charles |last2=Arthur |title=Apple iPad: the wait is over \u2013 but is it future of media or oversized phone? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2010/jan/27/apple-ipad-tablet-computer-kindle |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=January 27, 2010 |accessdate=February 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Apps ==\n{{Main|App Store (iOS)}}\nOn July 10, 2008, Apple introduced native [[mobile app]]s for its [[iOS]] operating system. On iOS, a dedicated App Store application served as the storefront for browsing, purchasing and managing applications, whereas iTunes on computers had a dedicated section for apps rather than a separate app.<ref>{{cite web |first=Lex |last=Friedman |title=The App Store turns five: A look back and forward |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/2043841/the-app-store-turns-five-a-look-back-and-forward.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=July 8, 2013 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> In September 2017, Apple updated iTunes to version 12.7, removing the App Store section in the process.<ref name=\"cutting the bloat\">{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Welch |title=Apple starts cutting the bloat from iTunes by removing iOS App Store |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/12/16298988/apple-itunes-desktop-update-removes-app-store |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 12, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jake |last=Smith |title=Apple's iTunes removes iOS App Store from desktop version |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/apple-removes-ios-app-store-from-desktop-versions-of-itunes/ |website=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=September 13, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> However, the following month, iTunes 12.6.3 was also released, retaining the App Store, with ''9to5Mac'' noting that the secondary release was positioned by Apple as \"necessary for some businesses performing internal app deployments\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Benjamin |last=Mayo |title=Apple still offers an iTunes version with App Store, Ringtones and other features removed in \u2018focused\u2019 iTunes 12.7 |url=https://9to5mac.com/2017/10/09/apple-itunes-apps-focused-removed-stopgap/ |website=[[9to5Mac]] |date=October 9, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Hardwick |title=Apple Quietly Releases iTunes 12.6.3 With Built-In App Store |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/10/09/apple-itunes-with-app-store-included/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=October 9, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== iTunes Store ==\n{{Main|iTunes Store}}\nOn April 28, 2003, Apple introduced the [[iTunes Store]], then-named \"iTunes Music Store\". It allowed users to buy and download songs, with 200,000 tracks available at launch. In its first week, customers bought more than one million songs.<ref>{{cite web |first=Brian X. |last=Chen |title=April 28, 2003: Apple opens iTunes Store |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/04/0428itunes-music-store-opens/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=April 28, 2010 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Music purchased was protected by [[FairPlay]], an [[encryption]] layer referred to as [[digital rights management]] (DRM).<ref>\n{{cite web |first=Daniel Eran |last=Dilger |title=How FairPlay Works: Apple's iTunes DRM Dilemma |url=http://www.roughlydrafted.com/RD/RDM.Tech.Q1.07/2A351C60-A4E5-4764-A083-FF8610E66A46.html |website=RoughlyDrafted |date=February 26, 2007 |access-date=December 16, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170927030905/http://www.roughlydrafted.com/RD/RDM.Tech.Q1.07/2A351C60-A4E5-4764-A083-FF8610E66A46.html |archive-date=2017-09-27 |url-status=dead |df= }}\n</ref> The use of DRM, which limited devices capable of playing purchased files,<ref>{{cite web |first=Dave |last=Hamilton |title=How iTunes Movie DRM-Removal Software Keeps Me Honest |url=https://www.macobserver.com/tmo/article/itunes-drm-removal-keeps-me-legal |website=The Mac Observer |date=September 2, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> sparked efforts to remove the protection mechanism.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jim |last=Tanous |title=The iTunes DRM Removal Saga: NoteBurner and a Look Back at Requiem |url=https://www.tekrevue.com/itunes-drm-removal/ |website=TekRevue |date=September 2, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Eventually, after [[Thoughts on Music|an open letter]] to the music industry by then-CEO Steve Jobs in February 2007,<ref>{{cite web |first=Arnold |last=Kim |title=Steve Jobs 'Thoughts on Music' - Asks for No Digital Rights Management |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2007/02/06/steve-jobs-thoughts-on-music/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=February 6, 2007 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Apple introduced a selection of DRM-free music in the iTunes Store in April 2007,<ref>{{cite web |first=Michael |last=Arrington |authorlink=Michael Arrington |title=EMI, Apple To Sell DRM-Free Music for $1.29/song |url=https://techcrunch.com/2007/04/02/emi-apple-are-announcing-sale-of-non-drm-music/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=April 2, 2007 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> followed by its entire music catalog without DRM in January 2009.<ref>{{cite web |first=Bobbie |last=Johnson |title=Apple drops DRM copy protection from millions of iTunes songs |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2009/jan/06/apple-drops-itunes-copy-protection |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=January 6, 2009 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2005, Apple announced that movies and television shows would become available through its iTunes Store, employing the DRM protection.<ref name=\"Movies in store\" />\n\n=== iTunes U ===\nIn May 2007, Apple announced the launch of \"iTunes U\" via the [[iTunes Store]], which delivers university lectures from top U.S. colleges.<ref>{{cite web |first=Peter |last=Cohen |title=iTunes U comes to the iTunes Store |url=https://www.macworld.com/article/1058118/itunesu.html |website=[[Macworld]] |publisher=[[International Data Group]] |date=May 30, 2007 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=McNulty |title=iTunes U comes to the iTunes Store |url=https://www.engadget.com/2007/05/30/itunes-u-comes-to-the-itunes-store/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[Oath Inc.]] |date=May 30, 2007 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nWith iTunes version 12.7 in August 2017, iTunes U collections became a part of the [[iTunes#Podcasts|Podcasts]] app.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tim |last=Hardwick |title=iTunes U Collections Will Move to Apple Podcasts From September |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/08/21/itunes-u-collections-to-apple-podcasts-september/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=August 21, 2017 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== iTunes in the Cloud and iTunes Match ===\nIn June 2011, Apple announced \"iTunes in the Cloud\", in which music purchases were stored on Apple's servers and made available for automatic downloading on new devices. For music the user owns, such as content ripped from CDs, the company introduced \"iTunes Match\", a feature that can upload content to Apple's servers, match it to its catalog, change the quality to 256kbit/s [[Advanced Audio Coding|AAC]] format, and make it available to other devices.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Ziegler |title=iTunes in the Cloud beta available today, iTunes Match lets you 'upload' the tracks you already own for $24.99 a year |url=https://www.theverge.com/2011/06/06/itunes-cloud-announced/ |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=June 6, 2011 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Courtney Boyd |last=Myers |title=iTunes Match: Apple announces its cloud based music service |url=https://thenextweb.com/wwdc/2011/06/06/apple-announces-itunes-in-the-cloud/ |website=The Next Web |date=June 6, 2011 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Internet radio and music streaming ==\n{{Main|iTunes Radio|Apple Music}}\nWhen iTunes was first released, it came with support for the [[Kerbango]] [[Internet radio]] tuner service.<ref>{{cite web |first=Tyler |last=Gray |title=Why Apple\u2019s iTunes Is Still Fundamentally Flawed, Even In iOS 7 |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3017628/why-apples-itunes-is-still-fundamentally-flawed-even-in-ios-7 |website=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] |publisher=Mansueto Ventures |date=September 18, 2013 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> In June 2013, the company announced [[iTunes Radio]], a free music streaming service.<ref>{{cite web |first=Doug |last=Gross |title=Apple arrives (late?) to music streaming with iTunes Radio |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/06/10/tech/web/itunes-radio-apple-wwdc/index.html |website=[[CNN]] |publisher=[[Turner Broadcasting System]] |date=June 11, 2013 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> In June 2015, Apple announced [[Apple Music]], its paid music streaming service, and subsequently rebranded iTunes Radio into [[Beats 1]], a radio station accompanying Apple Music.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Ben |last1=Popper |first2=Micah |last2=Singleton |title=Apple announces its streaming music service, Apple Music |url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/6/8/8729481/apple-music-streaming-service-wwdc-15 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=June 8, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== iPhone connectivity ==\n{{Update section|date=March 2020|reson=iPhone Backup, Restore, USB hotspot are amongst features that require iTunes to be installed on Windows.}}\niTunes was used to activate early [[iPhone]] models. Beginning with the [[iPhone 3G]] in June 2008, activation did not require iTunes, making use of activation at point of sale.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jonathan |last=Geller |title=iPhone 3G: the details you never wanted to know |url=http://bgr.com/2008/06/09/iphone-3g-the-details-you-never-wanted-to-know/ |website=[[Boy Genius Report|BGR]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |date=June 9, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Ping ==\n{{Main|iTunes Ping}}\nWith the release of iTunes 10 in September 2010, Apple announced [[iTunes Ping]], which then-CEO Steve Jobs described as \"social music discovery\". It had features reminiscent of [[Facebook]], including profiles and the ability to follow other users.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chloe |last=Albanesius |title=Apple Goes Social with 'Ping' Inside iTunes 10 |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2368579,00.asp |website=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=September 1, 2010 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Ping was discontinued in September 2012.<ref>{{cite web |first=Angela |last=Moscaritolo |title=Apple Shutting Down iTunes Ping on Sept. 30 |url=http://uk.pcmag.com/music-products/60441/news/apple-shutting-down-itunes-ping-on-sept-30 |website=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=September 13, 2012 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\n\n=== Security ===\n''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]'' reported in November 2011 that Apple had been aware of a [[security vulnerability]] since 2008 that would let unauthorized third parties install \"updates\" to users' iTunes software. Apple fixed the issue prior to the ''Telegraph''{{'}}s report, and told the media that \"The security and privacy of our users is extremely important\", though this was questioned by security researcher [[Brian Krebs]], who told the publication that \"A prominent security researcher warned Apple about this dangerous vulnerability in mid-2008, yet the company waited more than 1,200 days to fix the flaw\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Christopher |last=Williams |title=Apple iTunes flaw 'allowed government spying for 3 years' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/apple/8912714/Apple-iTunes-flaw-allowed-government-spying-for-3-years.html |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] |date=November 24, 2011 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\n=== Software bloat ===\niTunes has been repeatedly accused of being [[Software bloat|bloated]] as part of Apple's efforts to turn it from a music player to an all-encompassing multimedia platform.<ref name=\"cutting the bloat\" /><ref>{{cite web |first=Amy |last=Wang |title=iTunes is 13 years old\u2014and it\u2019s still awful |url=https://qz.com/666078/itunes-is-13-years-old-today-and-its-still-awful/ |website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] |publisher=[[Atlantic Media]] |date=April 28, 2016 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Ben |last=Lovejoy |title=Opinion: iTunes is now so clunky the only safe solution is to nuke it from orbit |url=https://9to5mac.com/2015/07/28/opinion-itunes-nuke-from-orbit/ |website=9to5Mac |date=July 28, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Robinson |last=Meyer |title=iTunes Really Is That Bad |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2015/07/why-is-itunes-so-bad/399833/ |website=[[The Atlantic]] |publisher=[[Emerson Collective]] |date=July 29, 2015 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Scott |last=Gilbertson |title=The top ten reasons iTunes sucks |url=https://www.wired.com/2008/11/the_top_ten_reasons_itunes_sucks/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Cond\u00e9 Nast]] |date=November 5, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref> Former ''[[PC World]]'' editor [[Ed Bott]] accused the company of hypocrisy in its advertising attacks on [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] for similar practices.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ed |last=Bott |title=Slimming down the bloated iTunes installer |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/slimming-down-the-bloated-itunes-installer/ |website=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=October 3, 2008 |accessdate=December 16, 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring the announcement of [[macOS Catalina]], [[Craig Federighi]] addressed the evolution of iTunes, and joked about the potential to include Email, Calendar, and Safari in iTunes before announcing iTunes's separation into independent apps, Apple Music, Apple TV, and more.\n\n==See also==\n* [[iTunes Festival]]\n* [[iTunes Store]]\n* [[iTunes version history]]\n* [[AirPlay]]\n* [[List of audio conversion software]]\n* [[Comparison of iPod managers]]\n* [[Digital distribution|Distribution Into iTunes]]\n* [[FairPlay]]\n* [[Feed aggregator]]s:\n** [[Comparison of feed aggregators|Feed aggregators, comparison]]\n** [[List of feed aggregators|Feed aggregators, List]]\n* [[Comparison of audio player software|Media players, comparison]]\n* [[Music visualization]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikibooks|iTunes}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.apple.com/itunes|iTunes}} \u2013 official site\n\n{{navboxes\n|title=iTunes\n|list1=\n{{Podcast distribution platforms}}\n{{Media player (application software)}}\n{{Apple software}}\n{{Apple software on Windows}}\n{{macOS}}\n{{Aggregators}}\n{{Apple}}\n}}\n\n[[Ca