{"title_page": "Josef Friedrich Schmidt", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = mogool. Schmidt\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1871|11|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Amberg]], [[Germany]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1948|9|28|1871|10|24}}\n| death_place = [[Munich]], [[Germany]]\n| known_for   = Inventor of [[Mensch \u00e4rgere dich nicht]]\n}}\n\n'''Josef Friedrich Schmidt''' (November 24, 1871 - September 28, 1948) was a [[Germany|German]] board game inventor.\n\n== Biography ==\n\n\nJosef copied the Indian [[board game]] called Pachisi and rebranded it [[Mensch \u00e4rgere dich nicht]], which loosely translates to 'man, don't get bothered'.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Schmidt Spiele]]\n\n== External links ==\n*\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schmidt, Joseph Friedrich}}\n[[Category:German inventors]]\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:Board game designers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = mogool. Schmidt\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date|1871|11|24}}\n| birth_place = [[Amberg]], [[Germany]]\n| death_date  = {{Death date and age|1948|9|28|1871|10|24}}\n| death_place = [[Munich]], [[Germany]]\n| known_for   = Inventor of [[Mensch \u00e4rgere dich nicht]]\n}}\n\n'''Josef Friedrich Schmidt''' (November 24, 1871 - September 28, 1948) was a [[Germany|German]] board game inventor.\n\n== Biography ==\n\n\nJosef copied the Indian [[board game]] called Pachisi and rebranded it [[Mensch \u00e4rgere dich nicht]]. He plagiarized the game in 1907/1908.{{Citation needed|reason=Reliable source needed for the whole sentence|date=July 2019}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Schmidt Spiele]]\n\n== External links ==\n*\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schmidt, Joseph Friedrich}}\n[[Category:German inventors]]\n[[Category:1871 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:Board game designers]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:1812:1c13:3400:c5b6:10ab:d86:80d", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eBiography)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josef_Friedrich_Schmidt"}
{"title_page": "Henry Menezes", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Henry Menezes\n| image          = https://images.app.goo.gl/4BHanUJa3S5n7zaz5\n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1964|4|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Mumbai]], India\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = 183 cm\n| position       = [[Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1    = 1979\u20131991\n| youthclubs1    = [[ Maharashtra ]]\n| collegeyears1  = 1983\u20131990\n| college1       = [[Maharashtra football team|Maharashtra]]\n| collegecaps1   = \n| collegegoals1  = \n| years1         = 1982\u20131983\n| clubs1         = Mafatlal sports club\n| caps1          = \n| goals1         = \n| years2        = 1983\u20131988\n| clubs2         = [[Bank of India]]\n| caps2         = \n| goals2         = \n| years3         = 1988\u20131995\n| clubs3         =  [[Mahindra United F.C.|Mahindra United]]\n| caps3         = \n| goals3         =      \n| totalcaps      = \n| totalgoals     = \n| nationalyears1 = 1985 -1992\n| nationalteam1  = [[India national football team|India]]\n| nationalcaps1  = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n\n'''Henry Menezes''' (born 30 April 1964 in [[Mumbai]]) is a former [[India national football team]] [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]],<ref>{{Citation|title=PART III. The Renaissance|date=1984-12-31|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9781400858088.241|work=Men and Ideas|pages=241\u2013342|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-5808-8|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> now the [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]] at the [[Western India Football Association|WIFA]] which is the governing body for football in the state of Maharashtra; affiliated to the [[All India Football Federation|AIFF]] and Deputy chairman of [[All India Football Federation|AIFF]] technical committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.footballparadise.com/the-renaissance-men-of-indian-football-henry-menezes-goalie-to-gamechanger-part-2/|title=The Renaissance Men of Indian Football - Henry Menezes, Goalie to Gamechanger Part 2|date=8 May 2017|publisher=|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.footballparadise.com/the-renaissance-men-of-indian-football-henry-menezes-goalie-to-gamechanger-henry-menezes-part-3/|title=The Renaissance Men of Indian Football \u2013 Henry Menezes, Goalie to Gamechanger Part 3|date=17 May 2017|publisher=|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.in/soccer/india/story/3622747/young-india-look-to-come-of-age-at-saff-championship|title=Young India look to come of age at SAFF Championship|date=3 September 2018|website=ESPN|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/sport/football/after-trials-the-test/articleshow/65892771.cms|title=AFC Championship: After trials, India to face first test against Vietnam|newspaper=[[Mumbai Mirror]]|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mangaluru/tech-fest-engineer-starts-at-nit-k-from-tomorrow/articleshow/66125202.cms|title=Technical fest 'Engineer' starts at NIT-K from tomorrow |newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nHenry is a former football player who play as a goalkeeper and his professional career started with Mafatlal sports club in mumbai at the age of 17 in 1982 . After spending one season he then moved to bank of india football team spend 5 years. In 1988 he joined mahindra united club and stayed there upto 1995 and his time at the club he was the captian of the club and won major trophies for the club and he also represented indian national football team. In mahindra he ended up his professional playing career and started his management career.\n\n==Managerial career==\nMenezes was the General Manager of Mahindra United Football Club, Mumbai which was disbanded in 2010, Menezes was instrumental in creating Mumbai FC and was the General Manager of [[Mumbai FC]] in the [[I-League]] prior to joining [[Mahindra United]] football club at the end of the 2006\u20132007 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/1064/i-league/2009/04/24/1226432/i-league-mumbai-fc-trio-put-in-their-papers|title=I-League: Mumbai FC Trio Put In Their Papers|date=24 April 2009|website=Goal.com|accessdate=23 November 2009}}</ref> Menezes is a [[Shiv Chhatrapati Award]] winner for excellence in sports.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.rediff.com/sports/2007/jun/28foot.htm|title=Mumbai Football Club launched|date=28 June 2007|website=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=23 November 2009}}</ref><ref>http://www.indianfootball.de/data/data.html</ref>\n\n===AIFF===\nHenry served different roles in football administration . He is the deputy chairman of [[All India Football Federation]]'s technical committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.in/soccer/indian-super-league/story/3666223/how-can-the-aiff-resolve-the-gourav-mukhi-controversy|title=How can the AIFF resolve the Gourav Mukhi controversy?|date=11 October 2018|website=ESPN|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref> He also worked as the Chief Executive Officer (CEO) at the Western India Football Association (WIFA) which is the Governing body for football in the state of Maharashtra.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/top-stories/Henry-Menezes-is-WIFAs-first-CEO/articleshow/7559243.cms|title=Henry Menezes is WIFA's first CEO |newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Menezes, Henry}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:India international footballers]]\n[[Category:People from Mumbai]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Henry Menezes\n| image          = https://images.app.goo.gl/4BHanUJa3S5n7zaz5\n| caption        = \n| fullname       = \n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1964|4|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Mumbai]], India\n| death_date     = \n| death_place    = \n| height         = 183 cm\n| position       = [[Goalkeeper]]\n| youthyears1    = 1979\u20131991\n| youthclubs1    = [[ Maharashtra ]]\n| collegeyears1  = 1983\u20131990\n| college1       = [[Maharashtra football team|Maharashtra]]\n| collegecaps1   = \n| collegegoals1  = \n| years1         = 1982\u20131983\n| clubs1         = Mafatlal sports club\n| caps1          = \n| goals1         = \n| years2        = 1983\u20131988\n| clubs2         = [[Bank of India]]\n| caps2         = \n| goals2         = \n| years3         = 1988\u20131995\n| clubs3         =  [[Mahindra United F.C.|Mahindra United]]\n| caps3         = \n| goals3         =      \n| totalcaps      = \n| totalgoals     = \n| nationalyears1 = 1985 -1992\n| nationalteam1  = [[India national football team|India]]\n| nationalcaps1  = \n| nationalgoals1 = \n| medaltemplates = \n}}\n\n'''Henry Menezes''' (born 30 April 1964 in [[Mumbai]]) is a former [[India national football team]] [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]],<ref>{{Citation|title=PART III. The Renaissance|date=1984-12-31|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1515/9781400858088.241|work=Men and Ideas|pages=241\u2013342|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-5808-8|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> now the [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]] at the [[Western India Football Association|WIFA]] which is the governing body for football in the state of Maharashtra; affiliated to the [[All India Football Federation|AIFF]] and Deputy chairman of [[All India Football Federation|AIFF]] technical committee.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.footballparadise.com/the-renaissance-men-of-indian-football-henry-menezes-goalie-to-gamechanger-part-2/|title=The Renaissance Men of Indian Football - Henry Menezes, Goalie to Gamechanger Part 2|date=8 May 2017|publisher=|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.footballparadise.com/the-renaissance-men-of-indian-football-henry-menezes-goalie-to-gamechanger-henry-menezes-part-3/|title=The Renaissance Men of Indian Football \u2013 Henry Menezes, Goalie to Gamechanger Part 3|date=17 May 2017|publisher=|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.in/soccer/india/story/3622747/young-india-look-to-come-of-age-at-saff-championship|title=Young India look to come of age at SAFF Championship|date=3 September 2018|website=ESPN|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://mumbaimirror.indiatimes.com/sport/football/after-trials-the-test/articleshow/65892771.cms|title=AFC Championship: After trials, India to face first test against Vietnam|newspaper=[[Mumbai Mirror]]|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/mangaluru/tech-fest-engineer-starts-at-nit-k-from-tomorrow/articleshow/66125202.cms|title=Technical fest 'Engineer' starts at NIT-K from tomorrow |newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\nHenry is a former football player who play as a goalkeeper and his professional career started with Mafatlal sports club in mumbai at the age of 17 in 1982 . After spending one season he then moved to bank of india football team spend 5 years. In 1988 he joined mahindra united club and stayed there upto 1995 and his time at the club he was the captian of the club and won major trophies for the club and he also represented indian national football team. In mahindra he ended up his professional playing career and started his management career.\n\n==Managerial career==\nMenezes was the General Manager of Mahindra United Football Club, Mumbai which was disbanded in 2010, Menezes was instrumental in creating Mumbai FC and was the General Manager of [[Mumbai FC]] in the [[I-League]] prior to joining [[Mahindra United]] football club at the end of the 2006\u20132007 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/1064/i-league/2009/04/24/1226432/i-league-mumbai-fc-trio-put-in-their-papers|title=I-League: Mumbai FC Trio Put In Their Papers|date=24 April 2009|website=Goal.com|accessdate=23 November 2009}}</ref> Menezes is a [[Shiv Chhatrapati Award]] winner for excellence in sports.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://in.rediff.com/sports/2007/jun/28foot.htm|title=Mumbai Football Club launched|date=28 June 2007|website=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=23 November 2009}}</ref><ref>http://www.indianfootball.de/data/data.html</ref>\n\n===AIFF===\nHenry served different roles in football administration . He is the deputy chairman of [[All India Football Federation]]'s technical committe.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.in/soccer/indian-super-league/story/3666223/how-can-the-aiff-resolve-the-gourav-mukhi-controversy|title=How can the AIFF resolve the Gourav Mukhi controversy?|date=11 October 2018|website=ESPN|accessdate=9 January 2019}}</ref> He also worked as the Chief Executive Officer (CEO) at the Western India Football Association (WIFA) which is the Governing body for football in the state of Maharashtra.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/sports/football/top-stories/Henry-Menezes-is-WIFAs-first-CEO/articleshow/7559243.cms|title=Henry Menezes is WIFA's first CEO |newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=10 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n==External links==\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Menezes, Henry}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:India international footballers]]\n[[Category:People from Mumbai]]\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: committe->committee", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Menezes"}
{"title_page": "Sista Afia", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Sista Afia|timestamp=20200418003458|year=2020|month=April|day=18|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Sista Afia|date=18 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Unreliable sources|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Ghanaian-born British musician}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| background      = solo_singer\n| image           = Sista afia pic.jpg\n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = Francisca Gawugah\n| alias           = Sista Afia\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1993|01|07}}\n| birth_place     = [[Accra, Ghana]]\n| origin          = Accra, Ghana<br>[[London, United Kingdom]]\n| genre           = [[Alternative rock]], [[Indie rock]],[[highlife]] and [[afrobeats]]\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| years_active    = (2015\u2013present)\n| label           = BK Records/Ace Kandi Records\n| associated_acts = [[Shatta Wale]], [[Medikal]], [[Kofi Kinaata]], [[Bisa Kdei]], [[Medikal]], [[Sarkodie (rapper)|Sarkodie]], [[Fameye]], [[Eno Barony]], [[Victor AD]]\n| website         = \n}}\n\n'''Francisca Gawugah (Duncan Williams)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.xbitgh.com/body-selling-point-sister-afia/|title=Your Body Is Your Selling Point \u2013 Sister Afia \u2022 XbitGh {{!}} Ghana's Hottest News Portal|website=www.xbitgh.com|access-date=2018-04-23}}</ref>''' (born 7 January 1993;  known by the stage name '''Sista Afia''') is a [[Ghanaian]]-born [[British people|British]] [[Indie rock]], [[Alternative rock]], [[highlife]] and [[afrobeats]] artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/I-was-afraid-of-Shatta-Wale-Sista-Afia-506187|title=I was afraid of Shatta Wale \u2013 Sista Afia|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.modernghana.com/music/35561/stop-comparing-me-to-efya-sista-afia-cries.html|title=Stop Comparing Me To Efya \u2013 Sista Afia Cries|website=www.modernghana.com}}</ref> She gained recognition following the release of her single \"Jeje\", which features [[dancehall]] artist [[Shatta Wale]] and Afezi Perry.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanamotion.com/sista-afia-jeje-ft-shatta-wale-x-afezi-perry-prod-willis-beatz/|title=Sista Afia \u2013 Jeje ft. Shatta Wale x Afezi Perry (Prod. by Willis Beatz)|date=20 December 2016|publisher=ghanamotion}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghxclusives.com/sista-afia-jeje-ft-shatta-wale-official-video/|title=Sista Afia \u2013 Jeje ft. Shatta Wale (Official Video)|website=www.ghxclusives.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanasongs.com/sista-afia-jeje-ft-shatta-wale-x-afezi-perry/|title=Sista Afia \u2013 Jeje (Ft Shatta Wale x Afezi Perry)|website=www.ghanasongs.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://dklassgh.com/2017/07/15/go-naked-attention-sista-afia/|title=I go naked for attention \u2013 Sista Afia|website=www.dklassgh.com}}</ref> She released her official debut single titled \"Kro Kro No\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deezer.com/en/album/13495871|title=Kro Kro No (feat. Bisa Kdei)|website=www.deezer.com}}</ref> This was followed by the singles \"YiWani\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Sista-Afia-s-YiWani-with-Kofi-Kinaata-receives-massive-endorsement-493691|title=Sista Afia's \"YiWani\" with Kofi Kinaata receives massive endorsement|website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ameyawdebrah.com/music-video-sista-afia-feat-kofi-kinaata-yiwani/|title=Music Video: Sista Afia feat. Kofi Kinaata \u2013 Yiwani|website=www.ameyawdebrah.com}}</ref> and \"Kofi\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pulse.com.gh/entertainment/music/new-music-sista-afia-kofi-feat-afedzi-perry-prod-by-willis-beatz-id5561560.html|title=New Music Sista Afia - Kofi feat. Afedzi Perry (Prod. by Willis Beatz)|website=www.pulse.com.gh}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\nSista Afia is an [[Afro-pop]] musician, and the niece of popular Ghanaian Bishop [[Nicholas Duncan-Williams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.a1radioonline.com/2017/07/27/i-cannot-be-like-my-uncle-duncan-williams-sista-afia/|title=I CANNOT BE LIKE MY UNCLE DUNCAN WILLIAMS \u2013 SISTA AFIA |website=www.a1radioonline.com}}</ref> She grew up in [[Accra]] and [[Kumasi]]. She attended Reverend John Teye Memorial Institute,Afia kobi Ampem GirGirlsand also Angel Educational Complex before relocating to the UK to further in nursing.\n\nSista Afia returned to Ghana in 2015 to start her music career. She was groomed by Ghanaian singer, [[Bisa Kdei]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xGJPEAT4a3s/|title=Sista Afia Ft Bisa Kdei - Kro Kro No |website=www.youtube.com}}</ref> and making their collaboration, Kro Kro No, her official first release as a musician.\n\n==Concerts/Shows==\n*Ghana Meets Naija 2017 Concert (Ghana Edition).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ghanaclassic.com/video-sista-afia-shatta-wale-performance-at-2017-ghana-meets-naija-concert/|title=Video : Sista Afia & Shatta Wale Performance At 2017 Ghana Meets Naija Concert|website=www.ghanaclassic.com}}</ref>\n*Ghana Meets Naija 2017 Concert (UK Edition).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pinkfmonlinegh.com/shatta-wale-and-sista-afia-at-ghana-meets-naija-uk-edition/|title=VIDEO: UNBELIEVABLE,SHATTA WALE AND SISTA AFIA AT GHANA MEETS NAIJA, UK EDITION |website=www.pinkfmonlinegh.com}}</ref>\n*Vodafone VIM launch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Sista_Afia&action=edit&section=2&editintro=Template:BLP_editintro/|title=VIDEO: SISTA AFIA PERFORMANCE IN CAPE COAST |website=www.ghanaweb.com}}</ref>\n*Ghana Meets Naija 2018 Concert (Ghana Edition).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/entertainment/Sista-Afia-delivers-erotic-performance-at-Ghana-Meets-Naija-2018-659003?video=1/|title=Video